	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Using regionally owned funds to deliver ‘aid for trade’</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 May 2009
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The ECDPM has produced a discussion paper looking at the ‘pros and cons’ of using regionally owned funds to deliver ‘aid for trade’ support to ACP regions. It sets out six key questions that need to be addressed in determining whether regionally owned funds would constitute an efficient and effective means of mobilising ‘aid for trade’, or whether they would simply complicate aid delivery by adding another layer to the administrative chain. Key questions to be addressed include:</p>
<ul>

<li>would a new regional fund have added value at this point in time in a particular region?</li>

<li>what kinds of projects should be financed?</li>

<li>how should resources be allocated among countries in a region?</li>

<li>how can efficient and transparent management be ensured?</li>

<li>what sources of funding are envisaged?</li>

<li>if large donor contributions are foreseen, is there a common understanding between members of the region setting up the fund and main donors on objectives and operationalisation of the fund?</li>

</ul>
<p>Clear political, technical and administrative choices will need to be made in all of these areas if regionally owned funds are to prove more efficient than existing aid delivery mechanisms. This is seen as particularly important, since it can take a number of years to set up the institutional mechanisms for the administration of regionally owned funds. The author of the ECDPM paper, in an article on the report written for <i>Trade Negotiation Insights</i>, concludes that ‘regionally owned funds offer a potential to improve the delivery of Aid for Trade in the medium term, but … further clarity is needed on which specific types of Aid for Trade measures in which specific regions could usefully be addressed through such instruments.’</p><p>A number of other reports on ‘aid for trade’ have recently been posted, notably the UN ECA ‘Global review on Aid for Trade 2009’ and the European Commission staff working paper ‘Aid for Trade monitoring report 2009’.</p><p>In addition, a major ‘aid for trade’ transport corridor initiative for the north-south transport corridor in eastern and southern Africa has recently been launched, with this being described by WTO director-general Pascal Lamy as a ‘perfect example’ of ‘aid for trade’ in action.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
ECDPM, <i>Discussion Paper No. 90</i>, April 2009 <br />
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/Braun-Munzinger_EN_080409_ECDPM_Regionally-owned-funds.pdf" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/Braun-Munzinger_EN_080409_ECDP...</a></p><p>
<i>TNI, </i>Vol. 8, No. 3, March 2009<br />
<a href="http://ictsd.net/i/news/tni/44038/" target="_self">http://ictsd.net/i/news/tni/44038</a></p><p>
UNECA <i>Global Review on Aid for Trade 2009, </i>March 2009<br />
<a href="http://www.uneca.org/eca_resources/Press_Releases/2009_pressreleases/pressrelease1809_global_review_trade_2009.pdf" target="_self">http://www.uneca.org/eca_resources/Press_Releases/2009_pressreleases/pre...</a></p><p>
EC, Commission staff working paper, (SEC) 2009, 442/2 <br />
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/EC_EN_080409_EC_Aid-for-trade-Monitoring-Report.pdf" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/EC_EN_080409_EC_Aid-for-trade-...</a></p><p>
WTO, Speech by DG Lamy, April 6th 2009<br />
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/news_e/news09_e/aid_06apr09_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/news_e/news09_e/aid_06apr09_e.htm</a></p><p>
EC<i>, </i>fact sheet, MEMO/09/150, April 3rd 2009<br />
<a href="http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2009/april/tradoc_142730.pdf" target="_self">http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2009/april/tradoc_142730.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>A critical question is whether a regionally owned fund would create more scope for funding the production, trade, employment and fiscal adjustment priorities which ACP governments and private sectors will need to get to grips with in the coming period? Would it in reality deliver aid more swiftly and more efficiently to the organisations and enterprises in member states that require ‘pump priming’ adjustment support? </p><p>In answering these questions, considerations linked to the day-to-day administration of aid need to be placed at the centre of the deliberations. How would such a regionally owned fund relate to existing procedures used by the main potential donors for the mobilisation and deployment of aid? How would it relate to the tendering procedures used by potential donors? How would it relate to potential donors’ procurement regulations? </p><p>Would the creation of a regionally owned fund actually serve to ease constraints in these critical areas of aid delivery and administration, or would they simply lengthen the time-frame between aid commitment and aid deployment on the ground at the national level? These are empirical questions which need to be answered in the context of the specific realities faced in individual ACP regions in the light of the aid procedures used by potential donors and innovations currently being introduced in aid deployment by these potential donors.</p>
		</div>
		
